text: I'm John Harwood with the New York Times
in CNBC this is a presidential
nomination race that's been largely
about numbers and most of them favorable
rock obama at this point over hillary
clinton he's raised more money he's won
twice as many states he has more
delegates that's the most important
indicator but now Hillary Clinton's
trying to introduce a new number to
change this race that's the victory
margin that she hopes to achieve here in
Pennsylvania in March she won the state
of Ohio which has some similar
demographics by 10 percentage points so
it's not out of the question that she
could do as well or better here in fact
Pennsylvania is one of the oldest states
in the country older voters have been a
key constituency for her it's also even
less affluent in the state of Ohio and
working-class White's have been a key
constituencies now Barack Obama is doing
everything he can to try to prevent her
from winning big he's out spending her
in television ads by more than two to
one and he's having events like this one
behind me here in suburban Philadelphia
we're trying to connect in a more
personal and intimate way with voters
than he has in some of the big rallies
early on Barack Obama's closed the gap
in some of the poll so far to make it a
single digit race he's hoping that
Hillary Clinton doesn't have the kind of
victory that allows her to make a new
argument to super delegates that she has
got momentum that Barack Obama can't win
the big states that Democrats will need
in the fall on the other hand it's not
likely that Barack Obama is going to win
this state either nothing in the polling
suggests that he has a lead or the
potential to get a lead in this state so
the odds are that if Hillary if polls
hold to form Hillary Clinton will win
this race at least by a single digit
margin and will go on for another two
weeks to the may six contests in North
Carolina and Indiana
